  "prompt": "What is the process of the three phases of the cellular respiration?",
  "response": "Cellular respiration is a metabolic process that converts biochemical energy from nutrients into adenosine triphosphate (ATP), the primary energy currency of cells. It consists of three main phases:\n\n1. Glycolysis (Preparatory Phase):\n- Occurs in the cytoplasm\n- Breaks down glucose (6-carbon molecule) into two 3-carbon pyruvate molecules\n- Produces a net gain of 2 ATP molecules\n- Generates 2 NADH molecules\n- Does not require oxygen (can be anaerobic)\n\n2. Krebs Cycle (Citric Acid Cycle):\n- Takes place in the mitochondrial matrix\n- Pyruvate is converted to acetyl-CoA\n- Acetyl-CoA enters the cycle and undergoes a series of chemical reactions\n- Produces 2 ATP molecules per glucose molecule\n- Generates 6 NADH and 2 FADH2 molecules\n- Releases carbon dioxide as a waste product\n- Requires oxygen (aerobic)\n\n3. Electron Transport Chain (Oxidative Phosphorylation):\n- Located in the inner mitochondrial membrane\n- NADH and FADH2 from previous stages transfer electrons\n- Electrons pass through protein complexes, creating a proton gradient\n- Generates approximately 34 ATP molecules\n- Oxygen serves as the final electron acceptor\n- Produces water as a byproduct\n\nThese phases ultimately convert nutrients into energy through a complex series of biochemical reactions.",
